    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a really solid starting point for them. I want to make sure they understand why it's so important, though. Could you add a bit more about why just having 'procedural' due process isn't enough? Like, why is having the right procedure actually a problem if the law itself is unfair?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Procedural due process only guarantees a fair *process*—like a proper trial—but it doesn't guarantee the *outcome* is just. If the law itself is fundamentally unjust or violates basic human dignity, a perfect legal procedure only legitimizes an unfair outcome. Substantive due process steps in to challenge the very substance of the law, ensuring that the government's actions align with fundamental, inherent rights, not just procedural rules. This is why it is essential for protecting true liberty.",
      "source": "target",
